.TH "BOTCTRL" "1" "November 23, 2025" "botctrl 2.0.x" "User Manual"
.hy
.SH BOTCTRL
.SS NAME
.PP
botctrl - Manage LifeBots and Corrade Second Life bots from the command
line
.PP
corrade - Manage Corrade Second Life bots from the command line
.PP
lifebot - Manage LifeBots Second Life bots from the command line
.SS SYNOPSIS
.PP
botctrl [-deih] [-a action] [-A avatar] [-l location] [-n name] [-k
apikey] [-T text] [-C channel] [-c corrade] [-F filter] [-M message] [-N
name] [-O name] [-S subject] [-s secret] [-u uuid] [-z num]
.PP
See the BotControl Github repository
README (https://github.com/missyrestless/BotControl) article for
additional information on the \f[V]botctrl\f[R] command and associated
tools.
.SS DESCRIPTION
.PP
A command line management system for \f[V]LifeBots\f[R] and
\f[V]Corrade\f[R] Second Life scripted agents (bots).
The \f[V]botctrl\f[R] command can be used to manage either
\f[V]Lite\f[R] or \f[V]Full\f[R] bots from \f[V]LifeBots\f[R] as well as
\f[V]Corrade\f[R] bots configured with the built-in Corrade HTTP service
enabled.
.PP
The \f[V]botctrl\f[R] command is installed as
\f[V]/usr/local/bin/botctrl\f[R] and symbolic links are created for the
commands \f[V]/usr/local/bin/corrade\f[R] and
\f[V]/usr/local/bin/lifebot\f[R].
When invoked as \f[V]corrade\f[R] the command uses the Corrade API to
control Corrade bots.
When invoked as \f[V]lifebot\f[R] the command uses the LifeBots API to
control LifeBots bots.
When invoked as \f[V]botctrl\f[R] the command can control either Corrade
or LifeBots bots, determining which API to use based on how the bot name
was specified on the command line:
\f[V]botctrl -c \[dq]bot name\[dq] ...\f[R] indicates use the Corrade
API to control a Corrade bot while
\f[V]botctrl -n \[dq]bot name\[dq] ...\f[R] indicates control of a
LifeBots bot.
.PP
See <https://lifebots.cloud> (https://lifebots.cloud) for more
information on \f[V]LifeBots\f[R].
.PP
See
<https://grimore.org/secondlife/scripted_agents/corrade> (https://grimore.org/secondlife/scripted_agents/corrade)
for more information on \f[V]Corrade\f[R].
.SS CORRADE CONFIGURATION
.PP
\f[B]NEW\f[R] The \f[V]botctrl\f[R] command now supports management of
both \f[V]LifeBots\f[R] and \f[V]Corrade\f[R] bots.
To manage a \f[V]Corrade\f[R] bot simply replace the
\f[V]-n <bot name or alias>\f[R] command line argument with
\f[V]-c <bot name or alias>\f[R].
.PP
In order to use the \f[V]botctrl\f[R] command to manage your
\f[V]Corrade\f[R] bot(s):
.IP \[bu] 2
The HTTP server must be enabled in the \f[V]Corrade\f[R] configuration
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]ScriptLanguage\f[R] must be set to \f[V]JSON\f[R] in the
\f[V]Corrade\f[R] configuration
.PP
Example snippet to enable the HTTP server in
\f[V]CorradeConfiguration.xml\f[R]:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
<Servers>
    <HTTPServer>
        <Enable>1</Enable>
        <Prefixes>
            <Prefix>http://+:8082/</Prefix>
        </Prefixes>
    </HTTPServer>
    ...
</Servers>
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Set the port number in the \f[V]Prefix\f[R] configuration to an open
unused port.
If you have more than one \f[V]Corrade\f[R] bot then use a different
port for each.
.PP
To set the \f[V]ScriptLanguage\f[R] to JSON in
\f[V]CorradeConfiguration.xml\f[R]:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
  <ScriptLanguage>JSON</ScriptLanguage>
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Note that each Corrade API request requires some permissions enabled in
the Corrade Configuration.
For example, balance inquiries and payments require the
\f[V]economy\f[R] permission, inventory operations require the
\f[V]inventory\f[R] permission, movement requires the \f[V]movement\f[R]
permission.
An example set of Corrade permissions that enable capabilities required
by the \f[V]botctrl\f[R] command might look like:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
    <Permissions>
        <Permission>movement</Permission>
        <Permission>grooming</Permission>
        <Permission>interact</Permission>
        <Permission>notifications</Permission>
        <Permission>talk</Permission>
        <Permission>group</Permission>
        <Permission>land</Permission>
        <Permission>inventory</Permission>
        <Permission>directory</Permission>
        <Permission>system</Permission>
        <Permission>bridge</Permission>
        <Permission>economy</Permission>
        <Permission>execute</Permission>
    </Permissions>
\f[R]
.fi
.SS CONFIGURATION
.PP
The \f[V]botctrl\f[R] command is installed in \f[V]/usr/local/bin\f[R]
along with some utility scripts for use with \f[V]cron\f[R] or other
management systems.
These utility scripts will need to be modified to suit your specific
needs, configuration and bot names.
You can modify the scripts in \f[V]bin/\f[R] and re-run
\f[V]./install\f[R].
.PP
Add \f[V]/usr/local/bin\f[R] to your execution \f[V]PATH\f[R] if it is
not already included.
.PP
Configure \f[V]botctrl\f[R] by adding and editing the file
\f[V]${HOME}/.botctrl\f[R].
.PP
At a minimum, you must configure your \f[V]LifeBots\f[R] developer API
key and bot secrets for the \f[V]LifeBots\f[R] bots you wish to control
using the \f[V]botctrl\f[R] command.
.PP
The following example entries in \f[V]$HOME/.botctrl\f[R] will allow you
to control your \f[V]LifeBots\f[R] bot named \[dq]Your Botname\[dq]
using the \f[V]botctrl\f[R] command:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
## Minimum contents of $HOME/.botctrl
#
# LifeBots Developer API Key
export LB_API_KEY=\[aq]<your-lifebots-api-key>\[aq]
# LifeBots bot secret
export LB_SECRET_Your_Botname=\[aq]<your-bot-secret>\[aq]
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Add an entry of the form
\f[V]export LB_SECRET_Firstname_Lastname=\[aq]<bot-secret>\[aq]\f[R] to
\f[V]$HOME/.botctrl\f[R] for each of your \f[V]LifeBots\f[R] bots.
.SS Example $HOME/.botctrl
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
#### BotControl Configuration ${HOME}/.botctrl
#
# Example BotControl configuration file for use with the botctrl command
#
# Configure API credentials for each bot and copy the file to ${HOME}/.botctrl
# For security make the file accessible by owner only:
#   chmod 600 ${HOME}/.botctrl
#
## CORRADE Command Control Configuration
#
#  To control Corrade bots from the command line you must configure a group, password, and URL
#
#  REQUIRED configuration parameters to control Corrade bots:
#      CORRADE_GROUP  CORRADE_PASSW  CORRADE_URL
#
export CORRADE_GROUP=\[dq]<your-corrade-bot-group-name>\[dq]
export CORRADE_PASSW=\[dq]<your-corrade-bot-group-password>\[dq]
export CORRADE_URL=\[dq]https://your.corrade.server\[dq]
export CORRADE_RANGE=\[dq]64\[dq]
export API_URL_bot1_name=\[dq]${CORRADE_URL}/bot1/\[dq]
export API_URL_bot2_name=\[dq]${CORRADE_URL}/bot2/\[dq]
# Default Corrade Bot Name, this name will be used if none is specified
export CO_BOT_NAME=\[aq]<bot1 name>\[aq]
##
## LIFEBOTS Command Control Configuration
#
#  To control LifeBots bots from the command line you must configure an API key and Bot secret
#
#  REQUIRED configuration parameters to control LifeBots bots:
#      LB_API_KEY   LB_SECRET
#      LifeBots bot secrets are unique to each bot. Aliases can be used for each, e.g.
#          LB_SECRET_BOT1_NAME
#
# LifeBots Developer API Key
export LB_API_KEY=\[aq]your-api-key\[aq]
export LB_SECRET=\[aq]your-bot-secret\[aq]  # Also referred to in the doc as an access code

# If you have more than one bot you can set each bot\[aq]s secret like this
export LB_SECRET_BOT1_NAME=\[aq]your-first-bot-secret\[aq]
export LB_SECRET_BOT2_NAME=\[aq]your-second-bot-secret\[aq]
export LB_SECRET_BOT3_NAME=\[aq]your-third-bot-secret\[aq]
# Replace spaces in the Bot\[aq]s name with \[dq]_\[dq]
# For example, if the Bot\[aq]s name is \[dq]John Doe\[dq] then the entry would be:
export LB_SECRET_John_Doe=\[aq]john-doe-bot-secret\[aq]

# Default LifeBots Bot Name and ID
export LB_BOT_NAME=\[aq]your-default-bot-name\[aq]
# LifeBots Bot ID
export LB_BOT_ID_Bot_Name=\[aq]lifebots-bot-id\[aq]

# OAuth Applications
# If you have configured OAuth applications then the client id and secret can be set here
export LB_CLIENT_ID_app_name=\[aq]your-oauth-app-client-id\[aq]
export LB_CLIENT_SECRET_app_name=\[aq]your-oauth-app-client-secret\[aq]

#### COMMON Settings used by both Corrade & LifeBots bots
# The following optional convenience entries are supported to allow
# specifying an alias on the command line rather than a SLURL or UUID
# All configured aliases can be listed with the command \[dq]botctrl -a alias\[dq]
#
# Second Life Bot ID
export SL_BOT_ID_Bot_Name=\[aq]secondlife-bot-id\[aq]
# Login siton UUID
export LOGIN_SITON_Bot_Name=\[dq]uuid-of-siton-object\[dq]

#### ALIASES
##
## Bot name aliases for use with the \[dq]-c name\[dq] and \[dq]-n name\[dq] command line options
export BOT_NAME_bot1=\[dq]Bot1 Name\[dq]
export BOT_NAME_bot2=\[dq]Bot2 Name\[dq]
export BOT_NAME_bot3=\[dq]Bot3 Name\[dq]

## SLURL aliases for use with the \[dq]-l location\[dq] command line option
# Slurl aliases can be set for use with the location option, -l location
# For example, the following 2 SLURL aliases could be used with -l beach or -l club
# to teleport the bot to the beach or the club specified in these SLURLs
export SLURL_beach=\[dq]http://maps.secondlife.com/secondlife/BEACH_REGION_NAME/X/Y/Z\[dq]
# Urlencode spaces in the region name by using %20 instead of space
export SLURL_club=\[dq]http://maps.secondlife.com/secondlife/CLUB_REGION%20NAME/X/Y/Z\[dq]

## UUID aliases for use with the \[dq]-u uuid\[dq] command line option
# UUID aliases can be set for use with the UUID option, -u uuid
# For example, the following UUID aliases could be used with -u dancepole
# or -u couch to seat the bot on the specified object
export UUID_dancepole=\[dq]dance-pole-object-uuid\[dq]
export UUID_couch=\[dq]couch-object-uuid\[dq]
\f[R]
.fi
.SS OPTIONS
.PP
The following command line options are available with \f[V]botctrl\f[R]:
.PP
\f[V]-a action\f[R] : specifies the API action (sit, teleport, login,
\&...)
.PP
\f[V]-l location\f[R] : specifies a location for login and teleport
actions
.PP
\f[V]-n name\f[R] : specifies a LifeBots Bot name, Default: Anya
Ordinary
.PP
\f[V]-c name\f[R] : specifies a Corrade Bot name, Default: Easy Islay
.PP
\f[V]-k apikey\f[R] : specifies an API Key, use environment instead
.PP
\f[V]-T text\f[R] : specifies the dialog button text for replies to
dialog menus
.PP
\f[V]-C channel\f[R] : specifies the channel for a message [default: 0]
.PP
\f[V]-F filter\f[R] : specifies a filter to match when listing
attachments
.PP
\f[V]-M message\f[R] : specifies the message body for a group notice/im
.PP
\f[V]-N name\f[R] : specifies the SL name of the recipient of an IM
.PP
\f[V]-O name\f[R] : specifies an attachment object name or outfit name
.PP
\f[V]-S subject\f[R] : specifies the subject for a group notice
.PP
\f[V]-s secret\f[R] : specifies a Bot secret, use environment instead
.PP
\f[V]-u uuid\f[R] : specifies a UUID for use with actions that require
one (e.g.
sit)
.PP
\f[V]-z num\f[R] : specifies a hover height adjustment size [default:
-0.05], can also be used to specify a payment amount
.PP
\f[V]-d\f[R] : indicates dryrun mode - tell me what you would do without
doing anything
.PP
\f[V]-e\f[R] : displays a list of supported commands and examples then
exits
.PP
\f[V]-i\f[R] : retrieves Bot details
.PP
\f[V]-h\f[R] : displays this usage message and exits
.SS Supported Actions
.IP \[bu] 2
Supported actions common to both Corrade and LifeBots:
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
activate_group, attachments, get_balance, get_outfit, get_outfits,
give_money,
.IP \[bu] 2
give_money_object, im, key2name, listinventory, login, logout, name2key,
notecard_create,
.IP \[bu] 2
rebake, say_chat_channel, send_group_im, send_notice, set_hoverheight,
sit, stand,
.IP \[bu] 2
takeoff, teleport, touch_prim, walkto, wear, wear_outfit
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
Supported actions for LifeBots only:
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
avatar_picks, bot_location, give_inventory, reply_dialog, status,
touch_attachment
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
Supported actions for Corrade only:
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
attach, conference, conference_detail, conference_list, createlandmark,
detach,
.IP \[bu] 2
fly, flyto, getattachmentspath, get_hoverheight, getmembersonline,
inventory cwd
.RE
.SS ENVIRONMENT
.PP
Entries in \f[V]\[ti]/.botctrl\f[R] can be \f[V]LB_API_KEY\f[R],
\f[V]LB_SECRET\f[R], or entries of the form \f[V]LB_SECRET_BOT_NAME\f[R]
in order to support multiple bots.
.PP
Entries can specify a Slurl alias.
For example:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
export SLURL_club=\[aq]http://maps.secondlife.com/secondlife/Scylla/226/32/78\[aq]
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
A Slurl alias can be used with the \f[V]-l\f[R] command line argument,
e.g.
\f[V]-l club\f[R]
.PP
Entries can also specify a UUID alias.
For example:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
export UUID_Mover=\[aq]xxxxxxxx-yyyy-zzzz-aaaa-bbbbbbbbbbbb\[aq]
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
A UUID alias can be used with the \f[V]-u\f[R] command line argument,
e.g.
\f[V]-u Mover\f[R]
.SS COMMANDS
.PP
The \f[V]botctrl\f[R] command supports a significant subset of the full
\f[V]LifeBots\f[R] API.
.SS Basic Commands
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]bot_location\f[R] : get precise bot location
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]key2name\f[R] : convert an avatar name to avatar UUID
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]login\f[R] : login bot
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]logout\f[R] : logout bot
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]name2key\f[R] : convert an avatar UUID to avatar name
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]status\f[R] : get bot status
.SS Movement Commands
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]sit\f[R] : sit on a specified object UUID
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]stand\f[R] : make bot stand up
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]teleport\f[R] : teleport bot to specified location
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]walkto\f[R] : walk bot to a location
.SS Communication
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]im\f[R] : send an instant message to an avatar
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]reply_dialog\f[R] : reply to a dialog menu (requires channel, UUID,
and button text)
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]say_chat_channel\f[R] : send a message to the specified chat
channel
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]send_group_im\f[R] : send an instant message to a group
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]send_notice\f[R] : send an official group notice to all group
members
.SS Inventory Management
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]get_outfit\f[R] : list currently worn bot outfit
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]get_outfits\f[R] : list available bot outfits
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]listinventory\f[R] : list bot inventory, optionally specify an
inventory folder UUID
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]set_hoverheight\f[R] : adjust bot hover height
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]takeoff\f[R] : remove a worn item
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]wear\f[R] : wear an inventory item (uses \[dq]add\[dq] rather than
\[dq]wear\[dq])
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]wear_outfit\f[R] : wear a specified outfit
.SS Group Management
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]activate_group\f[R] : activate a group tag
.SS Money & Transactions
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]get_balance\f[R] : get your bot\[aq]s L$ balance
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]give_money\f[R] : pay another avatar L$ from your bot
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]give_money_object\f[R] : pay an object L$ from your bot
.SS Object Interaction
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]attachments\f[R] : list bot attachments, optionally specify a
filter to match
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]touch_attachment\f[R] : touch a specified bot attachment
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]touch_prim\f[R] : touch a specified object by UUID
.SS Lifebot Configuration
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]listalias\f[R] : list configured \f[V]lifebot\f[R] aliases in
\f[V]$HOME/.botctrl\f[R]
.SS EXAMPLES
.PP
\f[B][NOTE:]\f[R] the examples below all assume you have configured
\f[V]$HOME/.botctrl\f[R] with your \f[V]LifeBots\f[R] API key and the
bot secret:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
# LifeBots Developer API Key
export LB_API_KEY=\[aq]<redacted>\[aq]
## John Doebot LifeBots secret
export LB_SECRET_John_Doebot=\[aq]<redacted>\[aq]
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
The following actions and commands, along with example command line
invocations, are supported by the \f[V]botctrl\f[R] command.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]activate_group\f[R] : activate a group tag
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : activate the specified group tag for bot
\f[V]John Doebot\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a activate -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -u \[dq]f8e95201-20af-b85f-a682-7ac25ab9fcaf\[dq]\f[R]
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
If \f[V]\[ti]/.botctrl\f[R] contains :
\f[V]export UUID_pay2play=\[dq]f8e95201-20af-b85f-a682-7ac25ab9fcaf\[dq]\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a activate -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -u pay2play\f[R]
.RE
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]attachments\f[R] : list bot attachments, optionally specify a
filter to match
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : list bot named \f[V]John Doebot\f[R] attachments
with name containing the string \f[V]HUD\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a attachments -F \[dq]HUD\[dq] -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]bot_location\f[R] : get precise bot location
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : get location of bot named \f[V]John Doebot\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a location -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]get_balance\f[R] : get your bot\[aq]s L$ balance
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : get the L$ balance of bot \f[V]John Doebot\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a balance -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]get_outfit\f[R] : list currently worn bot outfit
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : list currently worn outfit of bot named
\f[V]John Doebot\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a get_outfit -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]get_outfits\f[R] : list available bot outfits
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : list available outfits for bot named
\f[V]John Doebot\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a get_outfits -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]give_money\f[R] : pay another avatar L$ from your bot
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : pay avatar with specified UUID L$300 from bot
\f[V]John Doebot\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a give_money -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -u \[dq]3506213c-29c8-4aa1-a38f-e12f6d41b804\[dq] -z 300\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]give_money_object\f[R] : pay an object L$ from your bot
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : pay a tip jar with specified UUID L$100 from bot
\f[V]John Doebot\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a give_money_object -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -u \[dq]47cb1fc7-8144-b538-6716-c723fb1332d6\[dq] -z 100\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]im\f[R] : send an instant message to an avatar
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : send IM from \f[V]John Doebot\f[R] to avatar
\[dq]Jane Free\[dq]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a im -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -N \[dq]Jane Free\[dq] -M \[aq]Hi Jane, do you want to meetup?\[aq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]key2name\f[R] : convert an avatar UUID to avatar name
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : use \f[V]John Doebot\f[R] bot to get avatar name of
specified UUID
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a key2name -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -u \[dq]3506213c-29c8-4aa1-a38f-e12f6d41b804\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]listalias\f[R] : list configured \f[V]lifebot\f[R] aliases in
\f[V]$HOME/.botctrl\f[R]
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : list all configured \f[V]lifebot\f[R] aliases
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a listalias\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : list configured \f[V]lifebot\f[R] bot aliases only
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a botalias\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : list configured \f[V]lifebot\f[R] location aliases
only
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a slurlalias\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : list configured \f[V]lifebot\f[R] UUID aliases only
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a uuidalias\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]listinventory\f[R] : list bot inventory, optionally specify an
inventory folder UUID
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : list inventory of bot named \f[V]John Doebot\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a listinventory -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]login\f[R] : login bot
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : login bot named \f[V]John Doebot\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a login -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]logout\f[R] : logout bot
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : logout bot named \f[V]John Doebot\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a logout -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]name2key\f[R] : convert an avatar name to avatar UUID
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : use \f[V]John Doebot\f[R] bot to get avatar UUID of
Missy Restless
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a name2key -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -N \[dq]Missy Restless\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]reply_dialog\f[R] : reply to a dialog menu (requires channel, UUID,
and button text)
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : click couch menu button \[dq]Male\[dq] on channel
99999
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a reply -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -C 99999 -T Male -u \[dq]a811d6fe-de59-2f4e-ee19-0cc48da48981\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]say_chat_channel\f[R] : send a message to the specified chat
channel
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : send a message on channel 0, visible to everyone
nearby
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a say -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -C 0 -M \[dq]Hi everyone, you look great\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]send_group_im\f[R] : send an instant message to a group
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : send IM to a group from bot named
\f[V]John Doebot\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a send_group_im -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -u \[dq]f7d3c1b9-a141-9546-7e2d-dfd698c5df7c\[dq] -M \[dq]Meeting at Noon SLT tomorrow\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]send_notice\f[R] : send an official group notice to all group
members
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : send group notice with subject and message from bot
named \f[V]John Doebot\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a send_notice -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -u \[dq]f7d3c1b9-a141-9546-7e2d-dfd698c5df7c\[dq] -M \[dq]Meeting at Noon SLT tomorrow\[dq] -S \[dq]Meeting Tomorrow\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]set_hoverheight\f[R] : adjust bot hover height
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : lower hover height of bot \f[V]John Doebot\f[R] by
0.05
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a height -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -z \[dq]-0.05\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]sit\f[R] : sit on a specified object UUID
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : sit bot named \f[V]John Doebot\f[R] on an object
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a sit -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -u \[dq]d46e217b-fb5c-4796-bae3-ea016b280210\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]stand\f[R] : make bot stand up
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : make bot \f[V]John Doebot\f[R] stand up
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a stand -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]status\f[R] : get bot status
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : get status of bot \f[V]John Doebot\f[R] (status is
default action)
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]takeoff\f[R] : remove a worn item
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : bot \f[V]John Doebot\f[R] remove the specified
inventory item
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a takeoff -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -u \[dq]d666e910-ba72-0c11-a66e-c3759d8af0f5\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]teleport\f[R] : teleport bot to specified location
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : teleport bot \f[V]John Doebot\f[R] to the aliased
location \[dq]club\[dq]
.IP \[bu] 2
Requires an entry of the following form in \f[V]$HOME/.botctrl\f[R]
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]export SLURL_club=\[dq]http://maps.secondlife.com/secondlife/Scylla/226/32/78\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a teleport -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -l club\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]touch_attachment\f[R] : touch a specified bot attachment
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : bot \f[V]John Doebot\f[R] touch attachment named
\[dq]HUD Controller\[dq]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a touch_attachment -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -O \[dq]HUD Controller\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]touch_prim\f[R] : touch a specified object by UUID
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : bot named \f[V]John Doebot\f[R] touch an object
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a touch_prim -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -u \[dq]f11781d0-763f-52f9-4e23-3a2b97759fa2\[dq]\f[R]
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
If \f[V]\[ti]/.botctrl\f[R] contains :
\f[V]export UUID_spoton=\[dq]f11781d0-763f-52f9-4e23-3a2b97759fa2\[dq]\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a touch_prim -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -u spoton\f[R]
.RE
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]walkto\f[R] : walk bot to a location
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : bot named \f[V]John Doebot\f[R] walk to X/Y/Z
coordinates 100/50/28
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a walkto -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -l \[dq]100/50/28\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]wear\f[R] : wear an inventory item (uses \[dq]add\[dq] rather than
\[dq]wear\[dq])
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : bot \f[V]John Doebot\f[R] wear the specified
inventory item
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a wear -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -u \[dq]d666e910-ba72-0c11-a66e-c3759d8af0f5\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]wear_outfit\f[R] : wear a specified outfit
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]Example\f[R] : bot named \f[V]John Doebot\f[R] wear the outfit
named \[dq]Business Casual\[dq]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a wear_outfit -n \[dq]John Doebot\[dq] -O \[dq]Business Casual\[dq]\f[R]
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
If \f[V]\[ti]/.botctrl\f[R] contains :
\f[V]export LB_BOT_NAME=\[aq]John Doebot\[aq]\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]botctrl -a wear_outfit -O \[dq]Business Casual\[dq]\f[R]
.RE
.RE
